Promises in JavaScript are like a way to handle asynchronous tasks (tasks that take some time to complete) in a more organized and structured way. Think of it this way - when you make a request to load an image or fetch some data from a server, these tasks don't happen immediately but instead take some time to complete. Promises help us manage these tasks by allowing us to specify what should happen when the task is completed successfully (a "resolve" function), or if there's an error (a "reject" function).

At its simplest level, a Promise is an object that represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation. When we create a new Promise, we pass in a function called a "constructor" function that contains the asynchronous operation. This constructor function takes a single argument, which is a callback function. Inside the constructor function, we can perform our asynchronous operation and then call the `resolve` or `reject` method with the result or error, respectively.

Here's a simple example:

```javascript
const myPromise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  // some async operation here
  const result = Math.random() > 0.5;
  if (result) {
    resolve('Success! ');
  } else {
    reject('Error! ');
  }
});

myPromise.then(value => {
  console.log(value);
}).catch(error => {
  console.log(error);
});
